description.undefined:
This is an extension of the OntoCookie ontology with concepts for Dark Patterns.

The OntoCookie ontology for semantically representing web cookies and cookie-based data sharing online.

abstract.value:
The OntoCookie ontology is a formal representation of the cookie domain. The ontology was built as a response to the lack of openly available semantic models for cookies. By following a top-down ontology engineering approach, the main classes describing cookies, their purpose, necessity, data subject giving consent for cookies, sub-classes and the relationships between them were defined.

In version 2.0, the OntoCookie ontology has been extended to represent various types of dark patterns encountered on cookie banners online. The extension of the ontology is part of the MSc thesis of Gabriela Kurteva, School of Computer Science and Informatics at Cardiff University, The UK.

In addition, the ontology extension utilising GConsent ontology public source  in collaboration with the original authors of the OntoCookie Ontology, namely Dr. A. Kurteva.

As per Article 15 of the GDPR, 'at the time when personal data are obtained", the user is provided with the purposes of the processing for which the personal data are intended as well as the legal basis for the processing; the legitimate interests pursued by the controller or by a third party.

In addition to the information referred to in paragraph 1, the existence of the right to request from the controller access to and rectification or erasure of personal data or restriction of processing concerning the data subject or to object to processing as well as the right to data portability; where the processing is based on point (a) of Article 6(1) or point (a) of Article 9(2), the existence of the right to withdraw consent at any time, without affecting the lawfulness of processing based on consent before its withdrawal;

In the case of this ontology, 'AlignmentOfPersonalData' is a concept as well as a tangible entity. To separate this distinction with relation to the data processing, the AlignmentOfPersonalData class represents the control individual perform in its complete state.

To link the AlignmentOfPersonalData with the Processing instance, use the  hascontrolover property.

HTTP cookies (also called web cookies, Internet cookies, browser cookies, or simply cookies) are small blocks of data created by a web server while a user is browsing a website and placed on the user's computer or other device by the user’s web browser. Cookies are placed on the device used to access a website, and more than one cookie may be placed on a user’s device during a session.
The 'Purpose' reflect the functionality and the level of neccessity a web cookies.

As per Article 12 of the GDPR, "the controller shall take appropriate measures to provide any information referred to in Articles 13 and 14, and any communication under Articles 15 to 22 and 34, relating to processing to the data subject in a concise, transparent, intelligible, and easily accessible form, using clear and plain language."

In this case, 'Environmental Contenxt' refers to the collective representation of location and a timestamp for instant of creation along with capturing the expiry of consent as either a instant of time or a duration attributes assisting of building compliant cookie notices that  legally provide users with clear information and freedom to exercise control over their data.

The 'Environmental Contenxt' is linked to the 'Consent' via the isUpdatedConsentFor, Instant via the atTime, Temporal Entity via hasExpiry properties.

As per Article 4(1) of the GDPR pertaining to the definition of Personal Data, 'Data Subject' is defined as an identified or identifiable natural person (‘data subject’); an identifiable natural person is one who can be identified, directly or indirectly, in particular by reference to an identifier such as a name, an identification number, location data, an online identifier or to one or more factors specific to the physical, physiological, genetic, mental, economic, cultural or social identity of that natural person.

The 'Data Subject' is linked to the 'Consent' via the isConsentForDataSubject and hasConsent properties.
The 'Domain' attribute signifies the site for which cookies are valied with every request for this domain or its subdomains.

As per Article 25 of the GDPR, taking into account the state of the art, the cost of implementation and the nature, scope, context and purposes of processing as well as the risks of varying likelihood and severity for rights and freedoms of natural persons posed by the processing, the controller shall, both at the time of the determination of the means for processing and at the time of the processing itself, implement appropriate technical and organisational measures, such as pseudonymisation, which are designed to implement data-protection principles, such as data minimisation, in an effective manner and to integrate the necessary safeguards into the processing in order to meet the requirements of this Regulation and protect the rights of data subjects.

In this case, 'Dark Patterns' is a safisticated design concepts used in online platforms to trick users into doing something they have not intended to such as giving up their privacy - substantial, moderate or minimal impacts on users’ decisions.
